google/gemini-2.5-flash-lite:nitro.text: The app feels slow. It is not the speech-to-text, it is the rewrite step. The rewrite waits for the large language model. This takes two seconds sometimes.
More settings create a maze. Support becomes impossible then. I want good defaults.
Measure p50 and p95 in the bakeoff. Do not measure only the average. The long tail frustrates users.
For light cleanup, it should keep mostly the same words. Remove filler words like "um" and "uh." Fix punctuation.
Pick the fast, stable model. If quality suffers, roll back. Change the processing level defaults in one file.
The report will show latency, cost, and pass rate by level. Each level will have a recommendation.
Make this a small executable. Call OpenRouter. Write JSON and Markdown.
If a model is missing or errors out, record it. Finish the run anyway. This allows for partial results.
Keep transcripts in the repository. They contain no user data. Keep the corpus small to minimize costs.
After selecting new defaults, update the documentation. Run strict builds and strict tests. This will prevent breakage.

qwen/qwen3-32b:nitro.text: The app feels slow. The problem isn't speech-to-text anymore. The rewrite step pauses. It waits for the language model. That wait can last two seconds.
Adding more settings creates a complex tangle. Support becomes unmanageable. I want defaults that work well.
We need to measure p50 and p95 in any bakeoff. The average hides the tail. The long tail—the high percentiles—annoys users.
Light editing keeps most words the same but fixes punctuation and removes fillers like "um" or "uh."
Choose the fastest stable model. If quality drops, adjust one file's default settings to revert.
Structure each report level as a table. List latency, cost, and pass rate as columns. Add a recommendation line at the end of each level’s table. Use clear headings for each metric.
No large framework. A single executable that calls OpenRouter directly. Produces JSON and Markdown output.
If a model is missing or errors out, log it and complete the run regardless to review the partial results.
Keep synthetic transcripts in the repo. Use no user data. Keep the corpus small. Low cost to run.
After selecting new defaults, update the documentation. Run strict builds and tests to avoid breaking anything.

I’ve been thinking about the app’s slowness.  
It’s not the speech-to-text anymore.  
The rewrite step waits for the language model.  
Delay: two seconds sometimes.
The problem with adding more settings is that it creates a tangle. Support becomes unworkable. I want defaults that work well.
For a bakeoff, measure p50 and p95. Don’t use averages alone. The long tail causes user frustration.
For light cleanup, it should keep the same words while fixing punctuation and removing filler words like "um" and "uh."
Choose the fastest, most stable model. If quality suffers, fix it by changing the processing defaults in one file.
I want the report to be easy to scan. Use a table for each level. Include latency, cost, and pass rate. Each table should have a recommendation line.
Don't make a big framework. Make a small executable. Let it call OpenRouter and write JSON and Markdown. No large frameworks. Keep it simple.
If a model is missing or fails, record the error and finish the run to see partial results.
We should use synthetic transcripts. Store them in the repo. Exclude all user data. Keep the corpus small enough to lower costs.
Select new defaults. Update the documentation. Run strict builds and tests. Prevent breakage.
